The Comprehensive Crisis in Lebanon
Beirut —— In retrospect, financial crises usually appear to have precursors before they occur; however, they rarely clearly indicate the direction of history.
Lebanon's current situation is no different, as a foreseeable crisis has plunged the country into a highly unstable state.
Since the end of Lebanon's long civil war (1975-1990), its economic and political systems have been supported by external borrowing, inevitably leading to a continuous rise in public debt.
At some point, inflows of foreign capital had to stop. This point arrived at the end of 2019, followed by a series of negative shocks.
This "sudden stop" of capital has brought about a severe triple crisis for the country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
Lebanon's current-account deficit has reached 25% of its gross domestic product, with its exports being too small to even cover the costs of necessary imports.
The second issue is fiscal.
Lebanon's public debt now totals more than 150% of its gross domestic product.
Government revenue is collapsing under the pressure of economic recession, with the budget deficit already very large, reaching 10% of gross domestic product in 2019 and still rapidly expanding.
Most importantly, Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
Main banks, as the main recipients of inflows of foreign capital, have invested heavily in Lebanese sovereign debt (averaging 50% of their investment portfolios), and are now basically insolvent.
Together, these crises have pushed Lebanon's economy into a deep abyss.
Companies eager for loans and imports have begun laying off workers or completely shutting down.
An economic recession could lead to a Great Depression in Lebanon.
The main capital source supporting Lebanon's fragile political economy is not oil, but remittances, which are invested due to high interest rates and a fixed exchange rate tied to the dollar.
It is therefore no surprise that there are signs of "Dutch disease" everywhere: deposits have grown to over 400% of gross domestic product, creating a wealth effect that has reduced the national savings rate to an unlikely level — 3% of gross domestic product.
Inequality is high and still rising.
Between 2000 and 2015, the real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50%, greatly weakening tradable industries.
Lebanon has been losing its educated youth due to the lack of exportable goods and services.
But more importantly, the large-scale inflow of capital allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their positions through patronage rather than performance.
These elites have exploited wealth in both the public and private sectors to establish a bloated patronage ruling group.
Although this ensured political stability in this originally chaotic region, it failed to meet basic needs.
Even electricity supply is discontinuous and unreliable, while the broader challenges facing the macroeconomy remain completely unsolved.
A financial crisis has triggered a political uprising.
A popular revolutionary movement has taken to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Nevertheless, so far, the country's regime has overwhelmingly favored the elite in its response to Lebanon's economic issues, indicating that this crisis may ultimately be "resolved" with the support of the poor and middle class, further consolidating sectarian politics.
For example, the state has refused to introduce capital controls, allowing the main shareholders of each bank, including ruling politicians, to decide how to allocate cash withdrawals.
In fact, this allows elites to transfer capital abroad, while ordinary citizens struggle to access their deposits.
In addition, the central bank has lowered deposit rates but not the interest rates on public debt, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite the continuous decline in international reserves, Lebanon continues to repay its external debt, which is mainly owed to domestic banks.
There are signs that it may begin to sell state assets at fire-sale prices to entities linked to the elite.
Meanwhile, the official exchange rate remains unchanged, while the elites allow themselves to obtain dollars at a low exchange rate, whereas ordinary citizens face the reality of a rapidly declining free-market exchange rate. The current free-market exchange rate is discounted by 40%.
When the state starts printing liras to pay public sector wages, depreciation will accelerate.
In fact, the central bank has already been paying interest on dollar deposits (which account for more than 80% of all deposits) in liras, thereby creating conditions for inflation to eliminate public debt.
By shifting the cost of debt reduction through "liraization" of deposits to depositors, who are shareholders, the banks' capital can basically remain unscathed.
If this scenario becomes a reality, Lebanon's middle class will significantly shrink due to the reduction of real wages and pensions and the liquidation of savings.
The emigration of educated young people will accelerate, and even the economic interests of the immigrant community — on which this system relies — will be harmed.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a poor population system, which can be controlled by increasingly cheap patronage.
Ultimately, Lebanon will find itself in a situation similar to that of Venezuela.
By contrast, the establishment of a new republic pushed by revolutionaries will take a completely different approach.
Revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, rather than abandon it.
They believe its performance is far below its potential, and performance, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, patronage, and inequality.
They hope to establish a vibrant high-tech industry, make agriculture more environmentally sustainable, position the country as a cultural power station, and create more synergy with the diaspora community.
To achieve these goals, the reform movement hopes to pursue an orderly reduction of public debt, which will be guaranteed by bank capital, and forcibly reduce deposits of depositors who hold more than 1% of total deposits, which account for over 50% of total deposits.
They support a moderate depreciation of the currency and a thorough improvement of the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corrupt practices and increased spending on social programs and infrastructure.
With the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable downturn will be alleviated.
The current infighting over the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is part of a larger struggle in the country's quest for a new political solution.
The financial crisis poses a fatal threat to the country; however, it also represents an opportunity for political change.
The future of Lebanon remains uncertain.
